    <main class="notes" id="notesRoot" role="main">
      <details open>
        <summary>
          <span class="summary-title">About the Author</span>
          <span class="summary-hint">Who wrote it?</span>
        </summary>
        <div class="section-content">
          <p><strong>Robert Arthur</strong> (1909–1969) was an American editor and author. Famous for mystery and detective stories, he created the popular series <em>The Three Investigators</em>. His stories are known for <strong>suspense, witty dialogue,</strong> and <strong>unexpected twists</strong>.</p>
        </div>
      </details>

      <details>
        <summary>
          <span class="summary-title">Characters</span>
          <span class="summary-hint">Who appears in the story?</span>
        </summary>
        <div class="section-content">
          <ul class="characters-list">
            <li><strong>Ausable</strong> — A secret agent; fat, ordinary-looking, with an American accent. Lives in a small French hotel. Extremely clever and quick-witted.</li>
            <li><strong>Fowler</strong> — A young writer who wants adventure and is initially disappointed by Ausable's ordinary appearance.</li>
            <li><strong>Max</strong> — A rival spy; tall and thin with a fox-like face. Overconfident and gullible; confronts Ausable and tries to steal secret papers.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </details>

      <details>
        <summary>
          <span class="summary-title">Summary</span>
          <span class="summary-hint">Plot in brief</span>
        </summary>
        <div class="section-content">
          <p>Fowler meets Ausable hoping for an exciting spy adventure, but Ausable looks ordinary and calm. When they return to Ausable’s hotel room, they find <strong>Max</strong> there with a pistol demanding a secret report on missiles. Ausable remains calm, invents a story about a <strong>balcony</strong> outside the window and that the police are expected. When a knock comes at the door, Ausable claims it's the police he called. Panicking, Max attempts to escape via the non-existent balcony and falls to his death. Ausable uses only his wit and presence of mind to win.</p>
        </div>
      </details>

      <details>
        <summary>
          <span class="summary-title">Themes</span>
          <span class="summary-hint">Underlying ideas</span>
        </summary>
        <div class="section-content">
          <ul class="themes-list">
            <li><strong>Intelligence over Physical Strength</strong> — Wit and presence of mind beat brute force.</li>
            <li><strong>Appearances vs Reality</strong> — A subtle reminder that real ability doesn't need dramatic looks.</li>
            <li><strong>Calmness in Danger</strong> — Staying composed helps you outthink an opponent.</li>
            <li><strong>Deception as a Tool</strong> — Words and imagination are used effectively as weapons.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </details>

      <details>
        <summary>
          <span class="summary-title">Important Quotes</span>
          <span class="summary-hint">Memorable lines</span>
        </summary>
        <div class="section-content">
          <blockquote>
            “And you thought spies are only in books?” — a line that highlights irony between expectation and reality.
          </blockquote>
          <blockquote>
            “That’s the police. I asked for protection.” — Ausable’s clever trick that triggers Max’s panic.
          </blockquote>
        </div>
      </details>

      <details>
        <summary>
          <span class="summary-title">Word Meanings</span>
          <span class="summary-hint">Difficult words explained</span>
        </summary>
        <div class="section-content">
          <dl class="word-list">
            <dt><strong>Accented</strong></dt>
            <dd>Marked by a foreign way of speaking.</dd>

            <dt><strong>Disillusioned</strong></dt>
            <dd>Disappointed after expectations are not met.</dd>

            <dt><strong>Balcony</strong></dt>
            <dd>A small platform outside a building.</dd>
          </dl>
        </div>
      </details>

      <details>
        <summary>
          <span class="summary-title">Moral / Message</span>
          <span class="summary-hint">What the story teaches</span>
        </summary>
        <div class="section-content">
          <p><strong>Presence of mind and intelligence</strong> are often more powerful than violence. Overconfidence can lead to a downfall (as seen with Max). The story shows that danger can be handled without violence if you think clearly and act cleverly.</p>
        </div>
      </details>

